{"parse":{"title":"Seclusion of girls at puberty","pageid":25836956,"revid":822112666,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>seclusion of girls at puberty</b> has been practised in societies around the world, especially prior to the early 20th century. In such cultures, girls' puberty held more significance than boys' due to <a href=\"/wiki/Culture_and_menstruation\" title=\"Culture and menstruation\">menstruation</a>, the girl's potential for giving birth, and widespread ideas of <a href=\"/wiki/Ritual_purification\" title=\"Ritual purification\">ritual purification</a> related to the sacred power of blood.<sup id=\"cite_ref-benedict_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-benedict-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> These societies practised various <a href=\"/wiki/Rite_of_passage\" title=\"Rite of passage\">rites of passage</a>, many of which lost their original forms or completely disappeared with the emergence of modern trends such as <a href=\"/wiki/Industrialization\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Industrialization\">industrialization</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Broude20051_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Broude20051-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Rites\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Rites</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Reasons_for_the_seclusion\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Reasons for the seclusion</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Preparation_for_womanhood\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Preparation for womanhood</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Superstition\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Superstition</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-7\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Rites\">Rites</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Seclusion_of_girls_at_puberty&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Rites\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Venus_figurine_cave_of_Laussel.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/20/Venus_figurine_cave_of_Laussel.jpg/220px-Venus_figurine_cave_of_Laussel.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"331\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/20/Venus_figurine_cave_of_Laussel.jpg/330px-Venus_figurine_cave_of_Laussel.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/20/Venus_figurine_cave_of_Laussel.jpg/440px-Venus_figurine_cave_of_Laussel.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2308\" data-file-height=\"3468\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Venus_figurine_cave_of_Laussel.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/Venus_of_Laussel\" title=\"Venus of Laussel\">Venus of Laussel</a></div></div></div>\n<p>Two rules were common in the seclusion of adolescent girls: the girl must neither touch the ground nor see the sun. According to <a href=\"/wiki/Sir_James_George_Frazer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sir James George Frazer\">Sir James George Frazer</a>, these rules also applied to <a href=\"/wiki/Divine_king\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Divine king\">divine kings</a> and priests. These divine kings were carried on shoulders by their underlings who walked upon tapestry or carpet. Scholars have speculated that the <a href=\"/wiki/Paleolithic\" title=\"Paleolithic\">Paleolithic</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Venus_figurines\" title=\"Venus figurines\">Venus figurines</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources\"><span title=\"The material near this tag may rely on an unreliable source. (May 2012)\">unreliable source?</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> are related to such puberty rites as they lack facial features (not seeing the sun), their tapered legs without feet (not touching the ground), and their <a href=\"/wiki/Adiposity\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Adiposity\">adiposity</a> (caused by seclusion).\n</p><p>Among puberty rites which Frazer described, many adhered to the above rules:\n</p>\n<ul><li>Once a girl from <a href=\"/wiki/Zulu_people\" title=\"Zulu people\">Zulu tribes</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/South_Africa\" title=\"South Africa\">South Africa</a> showed the first signs of puberty, she had to cover her head with her blanket and hide among the reeds by the river until the sunset. Afterward, she had to stay in a hut for some time before coming back to the society.<sup id=\"cite_ref-frazer_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-frazer-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>In <a href=\"/wiki/New_Ireland_(island)\" title=\"New Ireland (island)\">New Ireland</a> and in the Kabadi District of <a href=\"/wiki/New_Guinea\" title=\"New Guinea\">New Guinea</a>, pubescent girls were kept indoors in seclusion for several years.<sup id=\"cite_ref-frazer_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-frazer-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>In many societies, including <a href=\"/wiki/Brahmin\" title=\"Brahmin\">Brahmins</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Bengal\" title=\"Bengal\">Bengal</a>, girls undergoing puberty were not allowed to see any males, not even their relatives. <a href=\"/wiki/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas\" title=\"Indigenous peoples of the Americas\">Native Americans</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/California\" title=\"California\">California</a> did not allow girls in their first menstruation to \"look about\".</li>\n<li>Among the <a href=\"/wiki/Tiyan\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Tiyan\">Tiyans</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Malabar_(Northern_Kerala)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Malabar (Northern Kerala)\">Malabar</a>, such girls were not allowed to catch the sight of a cow or touch \"any other person, tree or plant\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-frazer_4-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-frazer-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>Among the Tukuna of the Northwest Amazon, the girl at puberty is kept in isolation for about three months while preparation for the ceremony is underway. During this time, she \"is believed to be susceptible to all varieties of supernatural power\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Lincoln_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lincoln-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"reference\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">:<span>50\u201352</span></sup></li></ul>\n<p>Frazer believed that the Greek myth of <a href=\"/wiki/Dana%C3%AB\" title=\"Dana\u00eb\">Dana\u00eb</a>, who was kept by her father in seclusion but was impregnated by <a href=\"/wiki/Zeus\" title=\"Zeus\">Zeus</a>, was related to girls' puberty rites.<sup id=\"cite_ref-frazer_4-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-frazer-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"reference\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">:<span>602</span></sup> Lincoln also finds parallels between the Greek myth about the abduction of Persephone and the seclusion of girls at puberty. According to him, the seclusion of Tukuna girls at puberty may be referred to as \"being in the underworld\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Lincoln_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Lincoln-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"reference\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">:<span>77</span></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reasons_for_the_seclusion\">Reasons for the seclusion</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Seclusion_of_girls_at_puberty&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Reasons for the seclusion\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Preparation_for_womanhood\">Preparation for womanhood</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Seclusion_of_girls_at_puberty&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Preparation for womanhood\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Such seclusion rites are linked to the social preparation of girls for womanhood and their roles as wives and mothers. During their seclusion, girls would be taught by older women about their future roles.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Broude20051_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Broude20051-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Parker1905_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Parker1905-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Superstition\">Superstition</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Seclusion_of_girls_at_puberty&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Superstition\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Frazer claims the reason for seclusion practises was the \"deeply engrained dread\" of \"menstruous blood\". The first appearance of menstrual blood caused more fear than subsequent menstrual cycles. These fears stemmed more from <a href=\"/wiki/Superstition\" title=\"Superstition\">superstition</a> related to the sacred power of blood than from hygienic issues or the possible spread of disease.\n</p><p>Among the <a href=\"/wiki/Apache_Indians\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Apache Indians\">Apache Indians</a>, \"the adolescent girls are not segregated as sources of danger, but court is paid to them as to direct sources of supernatural blessing\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-benedict_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-benedict-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> A girl at her first menstruation was considered to be possessed of \"a degree of supernatural power\" which, though not entirely malevolent, still aroused feelings of the \"power of evil\".\n</p><p>The <a href=\"/wiki/Bushmen\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bushmen\">Bushmen</a> of South Africa believed that making eye contact with a girl during this period would make men \"fixed in whatever position they happen to occupy\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-frazer_4-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-frazer-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In earlier societies, some pubescent girls might have shown some unusual behaviours, giving rise to superstitions. Such behaviours could have been triggered by a number of factors; for example, pubescent girls are more prone to <a href=\"/wiki/Depression_(mood)\" title=\"Depression (mood)\">depressive</a> episodes than boys of a similar age. Historical records also show that these girls may have been subjects of <a href=\"/wiki/Incest\" title=\"Incest\">incestuous relationships</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Child_abuse\" title=\"Child abuse\">abuse</a>, triggering abnormal behaviours.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Arachige2009_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Arachige2009-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Seclusion_of_girls_at_puberty&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Menstrual_taboo\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Menstrual taboo\">Menstrual taboo</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Menstruation_and_culture\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Menstruation and culture\">Menstruation and culture</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Menarche\" title=\"Menarche\">Menarche</a>, a girl's first menstrual period</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Seclusion_of_girls_at_puberty&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-benedict-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-benedict_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-benedict_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Benedict, Ruth (2002). \"The Diversity of Cultures\".  In Spillman, Lyn. <i>Cultural Sociology</i>. Blackwell Publishers Ltd. p.&#160;22. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-631-21652-9\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-631-21652-9\">0-631-21652-9</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=The+Diversity+of+Cultures&amp;rft.btitle=Cultural+Sociology&amp;rft.pages=22&amp;rft.pub=Blackwell+Publishers+Ltd&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.isbn=0-631-21652-9&amp;rft.au=Benedict%2C+Ruth&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASeclusion+of+girls+at+puberty\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Broude20051-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Broude20051_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Broude20051_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Broude, Ruth (2005). \"Initiation and Rites of Passage\".  In McNeill, W. H.; Bentley, Jerry H. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://BerkshireWorldHistory.com\"><i>The Birkshire Encyclopedia of World History</i></a>. Berkshire Publishing Group. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-9743091-0-9\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-9743091-0-9\">0-9743091-0-9</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Initiation+and+Rites+of+Passage&amp;rft.btitle=The+Birkshire+Encyclopedia+of+World+History&amp;rft.pub=Berkshire+Publishing+Group&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.isbn=0-9743091-0-9&amp;rft.au=Broude%2C+Ruth&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2FBerkshireWorldHistory.com&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASeclusion+of+girls+at+puberty\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.thelureofnoma.com/?p=131\">\"Seclusion of Girls \u2013 Evidence from Paleolithic Times?\"</a>. 13 November 2012.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Seclusion+of+Girls+%E2%80%93+Evidence+from+Paleolithic+Times%3F&amp;rft.date=2012-11-13&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thelureofnoma.com%2F%3Fp%3D131&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASeclusion+of+girls+at+puberty\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-frazer-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-frazer_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-frazer_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-frazer_4-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-frazer_4-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-frazer_4-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Frazer, James (1993). \"Between Heaven and Earth\". <i>The Golden Bough: A Study in Magic and Religion</i>. Wordsworth Editions Ltd. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/1-85326-310-9\" title=\"Special:BookSources/1-85326-310-9\">1-85326-310-9</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.atitle=Between+Heaven+and+Earth&amp;rft.btitle=The+Golden+Bough%3A+A+Study+in+Magic+and+Religion&amp;rft.pub=Wordsworth+Editions+Ltd&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft.isbn=1-85326-310-9&amp;rft.au=Frazer%2C+James&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASeclusion+of+girls+at+puberty\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Lincoln-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Lincoln_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Lincoln_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Lincoln, Bruce (1981). <i>Emerging from the Chrysalis: Studies in Rituals of Women'